1
00:00:02,131 --> 00:00:05,712
Welcome to this final week of
the machine learning specialization.

2
00:00:05,712 --> 00:00:09,399
It's a little bit bittersweet for
me that we're approaching the end of this

3
00:00:09,399 --> 00:00:12,223
specialization, but
I'm looking forward to this week,

4
00:00:12,223 --> 00:00:15,641
sharing with you some exciting
ideas about reinforcement learning.

5
00:00:15,641 --> 00:00:20,195
In machine learning, reinforcement
learning is one of those ideas that while

6
00:00:20,195 --> 00:00:23,921
not very widely applied in
commercial applications yet today,

7
00:00:23,921 --> 00:00:26,407
is one of the pillars of machine learning.

8
00:00:26,407 --> 00:00:31,640
And has lots of exciting research backing
it up and improving it every single day.

9
00:00:31,640 --> 00:00:36,040
So let's start by taking a look at
what is reinforcement learning.

10
00:00:36,040 --> 00:00:38,040
Let's start with an example.

11
00:00:38,040 --> 00:00:41,029
Here's a picture of
an autonomous helicopter.

12
00:00:41,029 --> 00:00:45,021
This is actually the Stanford autonomous
helicopter, weighs 32 pounds and

13
00:00:45,021 --> 00:00:47,448
it's actually sitting
in my office right now.

14
00:00:47,448 --> 00:00:51,850
Like many other autonomous helicopters,
it's instrumented with an onboard

15
00:00:51,850 --> 00:00:54,984
computer, GPS, accelerometers,
and gyroscopes and

16
00:00:54,984 --> 00:00:59,196
the magnetic compass so it knows where
it is at all times quite accurately.

17
00:00:59,196 --> 00:01:02,996
And if I were to give you
the keys to this helicopter and

18
00:01:02,996 --> 00:01:06,974
ask you to write a program to fly it,
how would you do so?

19
00:01:06,974 --> 00:01:11,357
Radio controlled helicopters are
controlled with joysticks like these and

20
00:01:11,357 --> 00:01:16,012
so the task is ten times per second you're
given the position and orientation and

21
00:01:16,012 --> 00:01:18,018
speed and so on of the helicopter.

22
00:01:18,018 --> 00:01:22,837
And you have to decide how to move these
two control sticks in order to keep

23
00:01:22,837 --> 00:01:25,290
the helicopter balanced in the air.

24
00:01:25,290 --> 00:01:25,980
By the way,

25
00:01:25,980 --> 00:01:30,606
I've flown radio controlled helicopters
as well as quad rotor drones myself.

26
00:01:30,606 --> 00:01:34,375
And radio controlled helicopters
are actually quite a bit harder to fly,

27
00:01:34,375 --> 00:01:36,761
quite a bit harder to
keep balanced in the air.

28
00:01:36,761 --> 00:01:39,807
So how do you write a program
to do this automatically?

29
00:01:39,807 --> 00:01:42,324
Let me show you a fun
video of something we got

30
00:01:42,324 --> 00:01:44,720
a Stanford autonomous helicopter to do.

31
00:01:44,720 --> 00:01:48,656
Here's a video of it flying under
the control of a reinforcement learning

32
00:01:48,656 --> 00:01:49,740
algorithm.

33
00:01:49,740 --> 00:01:51,910
And let me play the video.

34
00:01:51,910 --> 00:01:54,178
I was actually the cameraman that day and

35
00:01:54,178 --> 00:01:57,380
this is the helicopter flying
on the computer control and

36
00:01:57,380 --> 00:02:00,940
if I zoom out the video,
you see the trees planted in the sky.

37
00:02:00,940 --> 00:02:02,893
So using reinforcement learning,

38
00:02:02,893 --> 00:02:06,230
we actually got this helicopter
to learn to fly upside down.

39
00:02:06,230 --> 00:02:07,990
We told it to fly upside down.

40
00:02:07,990 --> 00:02:12,938
And so reinforced learning has been
used to get helicopters to fly a wide

41
00:02:12,938 --> 00:02:16,940
range of stunts or
we call them aerobatic maneuvers.

42
00:02:16,940 --> 00:02:19,540
By the way, if you're interested
in seeing other videos,

43
00:02:19,540 --> 00:02:21,740
you can also check them out at this URL.

44
00:02:21,740 --> 00:02:27,844
So how do you get a helicopter to fly
itself using reinforcement learning?

45
00:02:27,844 --> 00:02:32,510
The task is given the position of
the helicopter to decide how to

46
00:02:32,510 --> 00:02:34,454
move the control sticks.

47
00:02:34,454 --> 00:02:39,437
In reinforcement learning,
we call the position and orientation and

48
00:02:39,437 --> 00:02:43,040
speed and so
on of the helicopter the state s.

49
00:02:43,040 --> 00:02:48,612
And so the task is to find a function that
maps from the state of the helicopter

50
00:02:48,612 --> 00:02:53,663
to an action a, meaning how far to
push the two control sticks in order

51
00:02:53,663 --> 00:02:59,640
to keep the helicopter balanced in
the air and flying and without crashing.

52
00:02:59,640 --> 00:03:05,390
One way you could attempt this
problem is to use supervised learning.

53
00:03:05,390 --> 00:03:09,440
It turns out this is not a great approach
for autonomous helicopter flying.

54
00:03:09,440 --> 00:03:15,155
But you could say, well if we could get
a bunch of observations of states and

55
00:03:15,155 --> 00:03:20,810
maybe have an expert human pilot tell
us what's the best action y to take.

56
00:03:20,810 --> 00:03:25,462
You could then train a neural
network using supervised learning to

57
00:03:25,462 --> 00:03:30,446
directly learn the mapping from
the states s which I'm calling x here,

58
00:03:30,446 --> 00:03:34,340
to an action a which I'm
calling the label y here.

59
00:03:34,340 --> 00:03:38,943
But it turns out that when the helicopter
is moving through the air is

60
00:03:38,943 --> 00:03:43,740
actually very ambiguous, what is
the exact one right action to take.

61
00:03:43,740 --> 00:03:47,074
Do you tilt a bit to the left or
a lot more to the left or

62
00:03:47,074 --> 00:03:50,590
increase the helicopter
stress a little bit or a lot?

63
00:03:50,590 --> 00:03:56,540
It's actually very difficult to get
a data set of x and the ideal action y.

64
00:03:56,540 --> 00:04:01,130
So that's why for a lot of task of
controlling a robot like a helicopter and

65
00:04:01,130 --> 00:04:05,645
other robots, the supervised learning
approach doesn't work well and

66
00:04:05,645 --> 00:04:08,640
we instead use reinforcement learning.

67
00:04:08,640 --> 00:04:14,302
Now a key input to a reinforcement
learning is something called the reward or

68
00:04:14,302 --> 00:04:19,697
the reward function which tells
the helicopter when it's doing well and

69
00:04:19,697 --> 00:04:22,040
when it's doing poorly.

70
00:04:22,040 --> 00:04:26,720
So the way I like to think of the reward
function is a bit like training a dog.

71
00:04:26,720 --> 00:04:29,939
When I was growing up,
my family had a dog and

72
00:04:29,939 --> 00:04:33,688
it was my job to train the dog or
the puppy to behave.

73
00:04:33,688 --> 00:04:35,719
So how do you get a puppy to behave well?

74
00:04:35,719 --> 00:04:38,970
Well, you can't demonstrate
that much to the puppy.

75
00:04:38,970 --> 00:04:43,318
Instead you let it do its thing and
whenever it does something good,

76
00:04:43,318 --> 00:04:44,701
you go, good dog.

77
00:04:44,701 --> 00:04:47,608
And whenever they did something bad,
you go, bad dog.

78
00:04:47,608 --> 00:04:52,032
And then hopefully it learns by itself
how to do more of the good dog and

79
00:04:52,032 --> 00:04:53,879
fewer of the bad dog things.

80
00:04:53,879 --> 00:04:56,830
So training with the reinforcement
learning algorithm is like that.

81
00:04:56,830 --> 00:05:00,495
When the helicopter's flying well,
you go, good helicopter and

82
00:05:00,495 --> 00:05:03,858
if it does something bad like crash,
you go, bad helicopter.

83
00:05:03,858 --> 00:05:08,223
And then it's the reinforcement learning
algorithm's job to figure out how to get

84
00:05:08,223 --> 00:05:11,918
more of the good helicopter and
fewer of the bad helicopter outcomes.

85
00:05:11,918 --> 00:05:15,662
One way to think of why
reinforcement learning is so

86
00:05:15,662 --> 00:05:20,376
powerful is you have to tell it what
to do rather than how to do it.

87
00:05:20,376 --> 00:05:25,278
And specifying the reward function rather
than the optimal action gives you a lot

88
00:05:25,278 --> 00:05:28,171
more flexibility in how
you design the system.

89
00:05:28,171 --> 00:05:33,739
Concretely for flying the helicopter,
whenever it is flying well,

90
00:05:33,739 --> 00:05:39,024
you may give it a reward of plus
one every second it is flying well.

91
00:05:39,024 --> 00:05:43,984
And maybe whenever it's flying poorly
you may give it a negative reward or

92
00:05:43,984 --> 00:05:50,160
if it ever crashes, you may give it a very
large negative reward like negative 1,000.

93
00:05:50,160 --> 00:05:54,135
And so this would incentivize
the helicopter to spend a lot more

94
00:05:54,135 --> 00:05:57,640
time flying well and
hopefully to never crash.

95
00:05:57,640 --> 00:06:00,045
But here's another fun video.

96
00:06:00,045 --> 00:06:05,971
I was using the good dog bad dog analogy
for reinforcement learning for many years.

97
00:06:05,971 --> 00:06:10,564
And then one day I actually managed
to get my hands on a robotic dog and

98
00:06:10,564 --> 00:06:14,917
could actually use this reinforcement
learning good dog bad dog

99
00:06:14,917 --> 00:06:18,718
methodology to train a robot
dog to get over obstacles.

100
00:06:18,718 --> 00:06:23,684
So this is a video of a robot dog
that using reinforcement learning,

101
00:06:23,684 --> 00:06:28,562
which rewards it, moving toward
the left of the screen has learned

102
00:06:28,562 --> 00:06:33,635
how to place its feet carefully or
climb over a variety of obstacles.

103
00:06:33,635 --> 00:06:37,796
And if you think about what it
takes to program a dog like this,

104
00:06:37,796 --> 00:06:41,078
I have no idea,
I really don't know how to tell it

105
00:06:41,078 --> 00:06:45,590
what's the best way to place its
legs to get over a given obstacle.

106
00:06:45,590 --> 00:06:50,530
All of these things were figured out
automatically by the robot just by giving

107
00:06:50,530 --> 00:06:52,734
it rewards that incentivizes it,

108
00:06:52,734 --> 00:06:57,040
making progress toward the goal
on the left of the screen.

109
00:06:57,040 --> 00:07:01,875
Today, reinforcement learning has been
successfully applied to a variety of

110
00:07:01,875 --> 00:07:04,962
applications ranging
from controlling robots.

111
00:07:04,962 --> 00:07:09,798
And in fact later this week in the
practice lab, you implement for yourself

112
00:07:09,798 --> 00:07:15,340
a reinforcement learning algorithm to
land a lunar lander in simulation.

113
00:07:15,340 --> 00:07:18,630
It's also been used for
factory optimization.

114
00:07:18,630 --> 00:07:23,258
How do you rearrange things in
the factory to maximize throughput and

115
00:07:23,258 --> 00:07:26,541
efficiency as well as
financial stock trading.

116
00:07:26,541 --> 00:07:31,312
For example, one of my friends was
working on efficient stock execution.

117
00:07:31,312 --> 00:07:35,487
So if you decided to sell a million
shares over the next several days, well,

118
00:07:35,487 --> 00:07:39,664
you may not want to dump a million shares
on the stock market suddenly because

119
00:07:39,664 --> 00:07:41,650
that will move prices against you.

120
00:07:41,650 --> 00:07:46,544
So what's the best way to sequence out
your trades over time so that you can sell

121
00:07:46,544 --> 00:07:51,840
the shares you want to sell and hopefully
get the best possible price for them?

122
00:07:51,840 --> 00:07:56,400
Finally, there have also been many
applications of reinforcement

123
00:07:56,400 --> 00:08:01,360
learning to playing games, everything
from checkers to chess to the card

124
00:08:01,360 --> 00:08:05,940
game of bridge to go as well as for
playing many video games.

125
00:08:05,940 --> 00:08:08,117
So that's reinforcement learning.

126
00:08:08,117 --> 00:08:12,126
Even though reinforcement learning
is not used nearly as much

127
00:08:12,126 --> 00:08:17,440
as supervised learning, it is still
used in a few applications today.

128
00:08:17,440 --> 00:08:22,046
And the key idea is rather than you
needing to tell the algorithm what is

129
00:08:22,046 --> 00:08:27,201
the right output y for every single input,
all you have to do instead is specify

130
00:08:27,201 --> 00:08:32,620
a reward function that tells it when it's
doing well and when it's doing poorly.

131
00:08:32,620 --> 00:08:37,511
And it's the job of the algorithm to
automatically figure out how to choose

132
00:08:37,511 --> 00:08:38,523
good actions.

133
00:08:38,523 --> 00:08:42,143
With that, let's now go into
the next video where we'll formalize

134
00:08:42,143 --> 00:08:46,274
the reinforcement learning problem and
also start to develop algorithms for

135
00:08:46,274 --> 00:08:48,260
